# Proposal: Project Final Stabilization

## Intent
Create a reproducible full-suite baseline for backend + frontend verification to improve release-readiness signal quality, without changing production behavior.

## Scope

### In Scope
- Define and document one canonical full-suite flow at repo root (backend + frontend commands, expected outcomes, prerequisites).
- Stabilization-only updates to test/config/docs/scripts that improve repeatability and log clarity.
- Targeted reduction of known expected-error test noise (e.g., duplicate-key logs) while preserving assertions and failure visibility.

### Out of Scope
- Any user-facing or API behavior change.
- Domain logic, schema, business rules, or feature development.
- Performance tuning outside test/runtime reproducibility.

## Capabilities

### New Capabilities
None.

### Modified Capabilities
None (no spec-level behavior changes).

## Approach
Follow minimal-risk sequencing: (1) codify baseline command contract, (2) align toolchain/command prerequisites for reproducibility, (3) harden noisy test logging narrowly at test scope only. Keep production codepaths and acceptance behavior unchanged.

## Affected Areas

| Area | Impact | Description |
|------|--------|-------------|
| `README.md` | Modified | Add canonical full-suite baseline/runbook and expected pass criteria. |
| `backend/pom.xml` | Modified (if needed) | Verification flow consistency only; no production behavior impact. |
| `frontend/package.json` | Modified (if needed) | Full-suite entrypoint/consistency only; no runtime behavior impact. |
| `backend/src/test/**` | Modified | Narrow test-log noise control for known expected-error paths. |

## Risks

| Risk | Likelihood | Mitigation |
|------|------------|------------|
| Local/CI environment drift still causes non-reproducible failures | Med | Pin/document Java/Node/tool versions and prerequisites in baseline runbook. |
| Over-suppressing logs hides genuine persistence regressions | Low/Med | Suppress only known expected signatures; keep errors/assertions and fail-fast behavior intact. |
| Baseline not adopted consistently | Low | Use one documented command contract and reference it in contributor workflow. |

## Rollback Plan
Revert stabilization-only commits (docs/test/config) and restore prior command definitions. Because production logic is untouched, rollback risk is limited to verification ergonomics.

## Dependencies
- Existing green local baseline (`mvn test`, `mvn verify`, `npm test`, `npm run build`, `npm run lint`).
- Consistent Java/Node/npm versions between local and CI.

## Success Criteria
- [ ] A single documented full-suite baseline flow exists and is reproducible on clean local setup.
- [ ] Full suite passes repeatedly with unchanged product behavior and unchanged functional assertions.
- [ ] Known expected-error test noise is reduced without masking real failures.
- [ ] CI/local verification outcomes match baseline expectations.
